prompt:
Tighten NixOS systemd hardening and add network allowlisting in the reel-life NixOS module.

## Context
reel-life runs as a systemd service on NixOS. It has an AI agent with API credentials. The service only needs to talk to three endpoints:
- localhost:8989 (Sonarr)
- api.anthropic.com (Claude API)  
- chat.googleapis.com (Google Chat webhook)

The existing NixOS module at `nix/module.nix` has basic hardening. We need to go further.

## What to build

### 1. Enhanced systemd hardening

Update the systemd service config in `nix/module.nix` to add:

```nix
serviceConfig = {
  # ... existing settings ...

  # Filesystem
  ProtectSystem = "strict";
  ProtectHome = true;
  PrivateTmp = true;
  PrivateDevices = true;
  ReadWritePaths = [ ];  # service is stateless, needs no writable paths

  # Kernel
  ProtectKernelTunables = true;
  ProtectKernelModules = true;
  ProtectKernelLogs = true;
  ProtectControlGroups = true;
  ProtectClock = true;
  ProtectHostname = true;

  # Capabilities
  CapabilityBoundingSet = "";  # drop ALL capabilities
  AmbientCapabilities = "";
  NoNewPrivileges = true;

  # Syscall filtering
  SystemCallFilter = [
    "@system-service"    # allow basic service syscalls
    "~@mount"            # deny mount operations
    "~@module"           # deny kernel module operations  
    "~@reboot"           # deny reboot
    "~@swap"             # deny swap operations
    "~@raw-io"           # deny raw I/O
    "~@clock"            # deny clock changes
    "~@debug"            # deny debugging
    "~@obsolete"         # deny obsolete syscalls
  ];
  SystemCallArchitectures = "native";

  # Security
  LockPersonality = true;
  RestrictRealtime = true;
  RestrictSUIDSGID = true;
  RestrictNamespaces = true;
  RestrictAddressFamilies = [ "AF_INET" "AF_INET6" "AF_UNIX" ];

  # Resource limits
  MemoryMax = "256M";
  CPUQuota = "50%";
  TasksMax = 32;
};
```

### 2. Network allowlist option

Add a module option for network restrictions:

```nix
allowedHosts = lib.mkOption {
  type = lib.types.listOf lib.types.str;
  default = [ "127.0.0.1" "::1" ];
  description = "IP addresses the service is allowed to connect to. Sonarr (localhost) is always allowed. Add resolved IPs for api.anthropic.com and chat.googleapis.com.";
};
```

Since systemd's IPAddressAllow works with IPs not hostnames, and Anthropic/Google IPs change, the pragmatic approach is:
- Use `IPAddressAllow` for localhost (Sonarr) 
- Document that for full network restriction, users should set up nftables rules
- Add an option `restrictNetwork` that when enabled, applies IPAddressAllow

```nix
restrictNetwork = lib.mkOption {
  type = lib.types.bool;
  default = false;
  description = "When enabled, restricts network access to allowedHosts only. Note: external API access (Anthropic, Google) requires adding their IP ranges.";
};
```

When restrictNetwork is true:
```nix
IPAddressAllow = cfg.allowedHosts;
IPAddressDeny = "any";
```

### 3. Sandboxing score

Add a comment in the module showing the expected `systemd-analyze security reel-life` score. After these changes it should be well below 5.0 (on the 0-10 scale where lower is better).

### 4. Documentation

Add a section to the module's comments explaining:
- What each hardening option does
- How to test the sandboxing: `systemd-analyze security reel-life`
- How to set up network allowlisting with nftables for full restriction
- The tradeoff: IPAddressAllow can't handle dynamic DNS, so external API access needs IP ranges or nftables

